<P>Mr. <HI>Sewall</HI>'s DISCOURSE Occa&s;ion'd by the DEATH OF HIS <HI>FATHER.</HI></P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="title page">
<PB REF="003351_0002_0FF81763A7C71B00" MS="y">
<P>THE <HI>Orphan's</HI> be&s;t Legacy: OR, GOD's Parental Care OF Bereaved <HI>Children:</HI> A DISCOURSE Occa&s;ion'd By the DEATH of the HONOURABLE <HI>Samuel Sewall</HI> <ABBR>Es;q</ABBR> Who departed this Life, <HI>Jan.</HI> 1. 1729, 30 <HI>Aetatis</HI> 78.</P>
<P>By His Son, <HI>Jo&s;eph Sewall,</HI> Pa&s;tor of the South Church in <HI>Bo&s;ton.</HI></P>
<BIBL>I&s;ai. xlix. 15.</BIBL>
<Q>Can a woman forget <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 span"> child, that &s;he &s;hould not have compa&s;&s;ion on the &s;on of her womb? yea, they may forget, yet will I not forget thee.</Q>
<BIBL>Chap. lxiii. 16.</BIBL>
<Q>Doubtle&s;s thou art our father, though Abraham be ignorant of us, &amp; I&s;rael acknowledge us not: thou O <HI>LORD,</HI> art our father, our redeemer, thy name is from ever|la&s;ting.</Q>
<P>BOSTON: Printed by <HI>B. Green:</HI> Sold by <HI>S. Gerri&s;h</HI> and <HI>D. Henchman,</HI> at their Shops. 1730.</P>
</DIV1>
</FRONT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="1" REF="003351_0003_0FF81765D8A48C48">
<HEAD>The Orphans be&s;t Legacy.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<BIBL>PSALM XXVII. 10.</BIBL>
<Q>WHEN my Father and my Mother for&s;ake me, then the LORD will take me up.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>_THE Title of this P&s;alm informs us who was the in&s;pired Penman, <HI>King David:</HI> In it he encourageth him|&s;elf in the LORD under his ex|treme dangers from his Enemies, and e&s;pecially from <HI>Saul. v.</HI> 1. <HI>The Lord is my light,</HI> the author of my joy, <HI>and my &s;alvation, whom &s;hall I fear</HI> &mdash;: And al&s;o offers to GOD his earne&s;t reque&s;ts for help and &s;uccour, as in the ver&s;e before my Text. <HI>Hide not thy face far from me &mdash; leave me not</HI> &mdash;. And the&s;e words may be brought in as an argu|ment to enforce his Petition from the con&s;ide|ration of his pre&s;ent &s;tate, That of an <HI>Orphan,</HI> who &s;tood in great need of help; or for the en|couragement of his faith, to tru&s;t in that GOD with whom the Fatherle&s;s find Mercy.</P>
<P>In the words we have, 1. <HI>A &s;orrowful ca&s;e &s;uppo&s;ed, When my Father &mdash;. <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> reads it, Becau&s;e my Father &mdash; &s;o it is an argument to enforce his Petition, that GOD would not leave him, nor for&s;ake him. <HI>Pi&s;cator</HI>
<PB N="2" REF="003351_0004_0FF817676B26EFA0">
and <HI>Mollerus</HI> read it, Altho'&mdash;. Our reading is, When: and thus <HI>Calvin.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2. We have <HI>his relief under this &s;orrow,</HI> Then the <HI>LORD will take me up:</HI> Receive, or gather me. Now we don't read that <HI>David</HI>'s Parents did ever de&s;ert him, tho' we find them &s;o unable to help him, and &s;o unfit to attend his Marches, that <HI>David</HI> de&s;ires of the King of <HI>Moab,</HI> that they might be with him till he &s;hould know what GOD would do for him, 1 <HI>Sam.</HI> 22.3. Accordingly, &s;ome Expo&s;itors take the words as &s;ignifying all humane helps under the Name of Parents, <Q>by which we may under&s;tand all Councils and Helps for &s;afety.</Q> Or, as others &s;uppo&s;e, <HI>His Parents had depar|ted this life;</HI> in which &s;en&s;e I wou'd now con|&s;ider the words. However it was, <HI>David</HI> was now like an <HI>Orphan,</HI> in an helple&s;s condition as to humane views and means, and accordingly he by faith realizeth GOD's Parental care and love, who, as He is ever able to help His Peo|ple, &s;o hath the bowels of a Father yerning to|wards them under their di&s;tre&s;&s;es; yea, more than the compa&s;&s;ions of the tender Mother. <HI>Then the LORD,</HI> the Name given to GOD here is <HI>JEHOVAH,</HI> which &s;ignifies GOD's Eternal Self-exi&s;tence, and His giving Being to all Creatures. The fathers of our fle&s;h are Mortal, and mu&s;t in a little time for&s;ake us, if we are not taken from them fir&s;t; but GOD the Everla&s;ting Father lives for ever to take care of His People. <HI>Shall take me up,</HI> or ga|ther me. When Parents are remov'd, the Fa|mily is ordinarily &s;cattered &amp; broken up; but
<PB N="3" REF="003351_0005_0FF8176934746010">
then GOD will gather the Children of His Peo|ple, and be a dwelling place to them.</P>
<DIV2 TYPE="doctrine">
<HEAD><HI>DOCT.</HI> It is the great Privilege of the Chil|dren of GOD, that when their be&s;t Friends and Helpers on Earth, their Fathers and Mothers for&s;ake them, He will take them up.</HEAD>
<LIST>
<ITEM>I. Our Fathers and Mothers mu&s;t for&s;ake us.</ITEM>
<ITEM>II. It is the Privilege of GOD's Children, that He will then take them up.</ITEM>
</LIST>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="proposition">
<HEAD><HI>Prop. I.</HI> Our be&s;t Friends on Earth, our Fa|thers and our Mothers mu&s;t for&s;ake us.</HEAD>
<P>GOD alone can &s;ay to us and fulfil that His word, <HI>I will never leave thee, nor for&s;ake thee.</HI> Our choice&s;t friends here are, as we, frail, mortal Creatures. For what is your life? it is even a vapour that appeareth for a little time, and then vani&s;heth away. <HI>Your Fathers where are they?</HI> &mdash; Zech. 1.5. They are no more in this World; they are gone to their long home, to the hou&s;e appointed for all living; and the Places which once knew them &s;hall know them no more. Accordingly, when the godly depart this life, they are &s;aid to be gather|ed to their People. Thus <HI>Abraham</HI> died in a good old Age, and <HI>was gathered to his Peo|ple,</HI> Gen. 2<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter">.8. <Q>When the Saints die out of this World, they are born into the other.</Q> Their bodies indeed are left behind; however, the condition of the&s;e is &s;uch when the Spirits that animated them are gone, that we mu&s;t
<PB N="4" REF="003351_0006_0FF8176BA142ADD0">
bury them out of &s;ight. And as their bodies re&s;t in their Graves, &s;o their Spirits return to GOD who gave them. When they leave our Society on Earth they go to the heavenly Je|ru&s;alem, to the Spirits of ju&s;t Men made perfect, and to Je&s;us the Mediator of the new Covenant. Here a little to confirm &amp; illu&s;trate this Head, I may &s;ay, 1. All Men are &s;ubject to the law of Mortality, and mu&s;t be remov'd out of this World by Death. 2. According to the cour&s;e of Nature Parents for&s;ake their Children, and leave them behind in this World, when they depart out of it by Death.</P>
<P N="1">1. <HI>All Men are &s;ubject to the law of Mor|tality, and mu&s;t be remov'd out of this World by Death.</HI> There is a Statute of Heaven for it, Heb. 9.27. &mdash; <HI>It is appointed unto Men once to die</HI> &mdash;. Indeed the LORD of Life hath made, and will make exceptions to this general rule. Thus <HI>Enoch</HI> and <HI>Elijah</HI> under the old Te&s;tament, were tran&s;lated, that they &s;hould not &s;ee death. (And &s;urely it was a great favour of GOD to the departed Spirits of the Saints, &s;o early to give them an Example of the glo|rious beauty and perfection which their bodies &s;hould be advanced to at the Re&s;urrection <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot"><HI>Enoch</HI> was tran&s;lated, A. M. 987. <HI>B. U&s;uer.</HI></NOTE>.) And the <HI>Apo&s;tle</HI> informs us that the People of GOD, who &s;hall be found alive at our Saviour's coming to rai&s;e the dead, <HI>Shall not &s;leep,</HI> (i.e. die) <HI>but be changed,</HI> 1 Cor. 15.51, 52. How|ever this is the common lot. P&s;al. 89.48. <HI>What man is he that liveth, and &s;hall not &s;ee death?</HI>
<PB N="5" REF="003351_0007_0FF8176F30E28AA8">
No &s;ooner had Man &s;inn'd but Death had power over him, and began to work towards a di&s;&s;olu|tion of this earthly frame. Gen. 2.17. &mdash; <HI>In the day thou eate&s;t thereof, thou &s;hall &s;urely die.</HI> And it is plain from Scripture that this Threatning Extends to <HI>Adam's</HI> Po&s;terity: Rom. 5.12. <HI>Wherefore, as by one man &s;in entred into the World, and death by &s;in; and &s;o death pa&s;&s;ed upon all men, for that all have &s;inned.</HI> Men are various ways di&s;tingui&s;h'd in the World into high and low, rich and poor, young and old, <HI>&amp;c;</HI> but in this re&s;pect they are all upon a level, equally &s;ubject to death. And this the Experience of all Ages teacheth. <HI>One Generation pa&s;&s;eth away, and another cometh;</HI> &mdash; Eccl. 1.4. Rom. 5.14. &mdash; <HI>Death reigned from Adam to Mo&s;es, even over them that had not &s;inn'd after the &s;imilitude of A|dam's tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion</HI>&mdash;. As <HI>infants</HI> who have not been guilty of Actual tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion com|mitted in their own per&s;ons, and yet the &s;en|tence of the law takes hold of them, an unde|diable evidence that <HI>Adam's</HI> fir&s;t &s;in is imputed to them; and that we all bring a corrupt Na|ture into the World with us. It is true, the Children of GOD are deliver'd from the &s;ting and cur&s;e of death by JESUS CHRIST, who by dying hath conquered this la&s;t Enemy; &s;o that they &s;hall all Triumph, and &s;ay, <HI>O death, where is thy &s;ling? O grave, where is thy victory?</HI> 1 Cor. 15.55. However, GOD will have them al&s;o ta&s;te of this bitter cup as a te&s;timony of His displea&s;ure again&s;t their &s;in, and as a means of purging away the remains of
<PB N="6" REF="003351_0008_0FF81771F55B5510">
it, that they may be pre&s;ented without &s;pot before Him. They mu&s;t pa&s;s thro' this <HI>Jor|dan</HI> before they obtain Re&s;t in the heavenly <HI>Canaan.</HI> Their Faith in JESUS CHRIST, and other Graces may help them to die well; but will not exempt them from the &s;troke of death: Heb. 11.13. <HI>The&s;e all died in faith</HI> &mdash;. They mu&s;t this way, thro' the valley of the &s;hadow of death, follow the Captain of their Salvation to Glory. They mu&s;t be bro't down to the du&s;t in order to their being exalted to &s;it with Him on Thrones in His Fathers King|dom. Their warfare is not accompli&s;hed till they have encountred this Enemy, nor can they &s;ay, It is fini&s;hed, until, with our Saviour, They give up the Gho&s;t. Thus died <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> the Ser|vant of the LORD. Thus <HI>David</HI> after he had &s;erved his generation according to the will of GOD, <HI>fell a &s;leep, &amp; was laid to his Fathers</HI> &mdash;. The matter of Fact which the Jews alledged was true, tho' mi&s;applied, Joh. 8.52. &mdash; <HI>Abra|ham is dead, and the Prophets</HI>&mdash;. Accordingly, when our Saviour a&s;&s;erts, <HI>If any man keep my &s;aying, he &s;hall never &s;ee death,</HI> v. 51. He mu&s;t be under&s;tood of the <HI>&s;econd death,</HI> which is eter|nal, comprehending the de&s;truction of Soul and Body in Hell. Now, by death we are remove'd out of this World, agreably death is call'd a departure, 2 <HI>Tim.</HI> 4. 6. &mdash; The time of <HI>my de|parture</HI> is at hand. The Soul goeth forth out of the Body, the vital union between them be|ing di&s;&s;olvd'd. <HI>Gen.</HI> 35.18. &mdash; As her <HI>&s;oul was in departing, for &s;he died</HI> &mdash;. And the Body is then carried to the Grave, the Hou&s;e appointed
<PB N="7" REF="003351_0009_0FF81775165B7AF0">
for all the living. Death di&s;&s;olveth the Union, and breaks off the Society there was between the neare&s;t Relations; they are &s;eparated for|ever as to what concerns this life, which leads me to &s;ay,</P>
<P N="2">2. <HI>According to the Cour&s;e of Nature Pa|rents for&s;ake their Children, and leave them behind in this World; when they depart out of it by death.</HI> Indeed, it is no uncommon thing to have this order of Nature inverted. We read that of old, <HI>Haran died before his Father Terah,</HI> i. e. "In his &s;ight and pre&s;ence, he being yet alive, <HI>Gen.</HI> 11. 28. Thus <HI>Aaron, Job, David,</HI> &amp;c. &s;urviv'd to bewail the lo&s;s of Children. And alas! how common is this in our day? Upon this account among others the land of darkne&s;s may be &s;aid to be <HI>without or|der,</HI> Job 10. 22. The young and &s;trong have the precedency oftentimes, and go to the Grave before the aged and infirm. The lamp of life is not &s;eldom blown out. Di&s;ea&s;es &amp; Accidents, as we call them, tho' all under the government of GOD's Providence, often put a period to lives which might endure much longer. We die &s;ooner or later according to the will of the Sovereign GOD, who hath determined our Days on Earth in His Decree, &amp; appointed our bounds which we cannot pa&s;s. Job 14.5. <HI>Seeing his days are determined, the number of his months are with thee, thou ha&s;t appointed his bounds that he cannot pa&s;s.</HI> However, according to the cour&s;e of Nature, as Parents are born into the World fir&s;t, &s;o they die out of it before their Children. The decays of Nature
<PB N="8" REF="003351_0010_0FF817772E876468">
and infirmities of Age gradually grow upon them; we &s;ee them decline and wear away un|der the fatigues and burdens of life, until, as the Candle burns down and goeth out, &s;o the vital heat and moi&s;ture being con&s;um'd, they expire. P&s;al. 90.10. <HI>The days of our years are three&s;core years and ten; and if by rea&s;on of &s;trength they be four&s;core years, yet is their &s;trength labour and &s;orrow: for it is &s;oon cut off, and we fly away.</HI> This hath been accoun|ted the Age of Man &s;ince <HI>Mo&s;es</HI>'s time. Here al&s;o we may ob&s;erve, That it is no &s;trange thing for Parents to be taken away in their full &s;trength, yea, even before middle Age, and &s;o to leave their Children Young, &s;ometimes not ca|pable of under&s;tanding the greatne&s;s of their lo&s;s; but then, others by the favour of GOD continue till their Children are grown up, and after that they have for &s;ome time experienc'd the great benefit of their Pre&s;ence, Coun&s;els and Prayers, the Parents die and leave them to la|ment their lo&s;s. And the pious Parent may when leaving this World, &s;ay to &s;urvivours, &s;omething as our Saviour to the daughters of Jeru&s;alem; &mdash; <HI>Weep not for me, but for your &s;elves</HI> <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Luck 23, 28.</NOTE>. For when &s;uch depart, they go to be with CHRIST, which is far better; they go out of a World of &s;in and &s;orrow to that better Country, which is an heavenly, where they are comforted in the glorious Pre&s;ence of the Lamb, having all tears wiped from their Eyes, and be|ing made perfect in holine&s;s. The Day of their
<PB N="9" REF="003351_0011_0FF8177B3478FFA8">
death is better to them than the day of their birth. But then, by &s;uch a bereaving Providence, GOD calls us to lament and mourn; for they are gone from us, and that not to return again to conver&s;e with us here. We &s;ee their faces no more; we behold their exemplary Conver|&s;ation no more, receive their In&s;tructions and help no more. And therefore &s;uch a Bereave|ment ought to be lamented, even tho' our Parents &s;hould live to a good old Age: When their hoary heads which were a Crown of Glory, being found in the way of righteou&s;ne&s;s, are laid in the du&s;t, We may well take up a lamentation, and &s;ay, the <HI>Crown is fallen &mdash; for the glo|ry of children are their fathers,</HI> Prov. 17.6. However, the Children of GOD have this Con|&s;olation when exerci&s;ed with &s;uch Bereavements, that tho' <HI>their Fathers</HI> are not, yet the GOD <HI>of their Fathers</HI> lives to take care of them, and fulfil the promi&s;es of His Everla&s;ting Co|venant: Which brings me to,</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="proposition">
<HEAD><HI>Prop. II.</HI> It is the great Privilege of GOD's Children, that when their Fathers and Mo|thers for&s;ake them, He will take them up.</HEAD>
<P>GOD is the everla&s;ting Father, and in CHRIST JESUS the Father of Mercies, and the GOD of all Con&s;olations to His Cove|nant-People. They that receive the eternal Son of GOD by faith, have <HI>power to become the &s;ons of GOD</HI> <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Joh. 1. 12.</NOTE> "They are received into this
<PB N="10" REF="003351_0012_0FF8177EC0F68178">
happy number, and have a right to the precious Privileges of &s;uch: They have the Spirit of Adoption, whereby they cry, <HI>Abba Father,</HI> and GOD pitieth them, as a father pitieth his Children. Yea, GOD hath more than the com|pa&s;&s;ions of the tender Mother: I&s;ai. 49.5. <HI>Can a woman forget her &s;ucking child, that &s;he &s;hould not have compa&s;&s;ion on the &s;on of her womb? Yea, they may forget, yet will I not forget thee.</HI> The love of the Mother, the more tender Sex towards her Offspring, is a &s;trong and con&s;tant affection indeed, e&s;pecially while the child hangs at her Brea&s;t; yet &s;uch are the moral and natural infirmities of humane Nature &s;ince the Fall, that even &s;he may forget &mdash; but GOD remembers His Children with an everla&s;ting Love, and is accordingly always ready to &s;uccour them under their &s;orrows, with the mo&s;t tender compa&s;&s;ion. I&s;ai. 66.13. <HI>As one whom his Mother comforteth, &s;o will I comfort you</HI> &mdash;. Our Lord JESUS CHRIST was with His Di&s;ciples as the Father of the Family while on Earth, and when the time of His departure drew nigh, one of the good words He &s;pake to them was that, Joh. 14.18. <HI>I will not leave you comfortle&s;s</HI> &mdash;: In the Original it is, <HI>Orphans,</HI> bereaved ones: When about to leave this World, as to His bodily pre&s;ence, He committed them to the care and protection of their heavenly Father. Joh. 17.11. <HI>Holy Father keep thro' thine own Name, tho&s;e whom thou ha&s;t given me</HI> &mdash;. And to &s;peak more directly of earthly Parents and Ance&s;tors; the People of GOD comfort them&s;elves from this con&s;ide|ration:
<PB N="11" REF="003351_0013_0FF8178139AE8E48">
I&s;ai. 63.16. <HI>Doubtle&s;s thou art our Fa|ther, though Abraham be ignorant of us, and I&s;rael acknowledge us not: thou O LORD, art our father, our redeemer, thy name is from everla&s;ting.</HI> Upon which a worthy Expo&s;itor ob&s;erveth, "That they own them&s;elves Father|le&s;s, if He be not their Father, and &s;o ca&s;t them|&s;elves upon Him with whom the <HI>Fatherle&s;s findeth mercy,</HI> Ho&s;. 14.3. It was the honour of their Nation that they had <HI>Abraham to their Father,</HI> Mat. 3.9. who was the friend of GOD; and <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> who was a Prince with GOD; but what the better were they for that, unle&s;s they had GOD Him&s;elf for their Father; for <HI>Abra|ham</HI> and <HI>I&s;rael</HI> can't help them, they have not the power that GOD hath, they are dead long &s;ince, and are ignorant of us, and acknowledge us not, they know not what our ca&s;e is, nor what our wants are, and therefore know not which way to do us a kindne&s;s &mdash;. <HI>But thou O LORD art our Father</HI> &s;till. The fathers of our fle&s;h may call them&s;elves <HI>Ever Loving,</HI> but not <HI>Ever Living;</HI> it is GOD only that is the immortal Father, that always knows us, and is never at a di&s;tance from us, and therefore <HI>our Redeemer, from everla&s;ting is thy Name,</HI> the Name by which we will know and own thee, it is the Name by which from of old thou ha&s;t been known; Thy People have always look'd upon thee as the GOD to whom they might appeal to right them, and plead their cau&s;e" <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Henry</NOTE></P>
<P N="1"><PB N="12" REF="003351_0014_0FF817830B1D5258">I would here very briefly &s;peak to a few par|ticulars, further to &s;hew the Privilege of the Children of GOD contain'd in that good word, <HI>The LORD will take me up:</HI> which word in the Original is ob&s;erv'd to be u&s;ed of <HI>taking up and bringing home a &s;tray &s;heep:</HI> Deut. 22.1, 2.</P>
<P N="1">1. <HI>When Father and Mother for&s;ake, GOD will as a tender Father take up his People, own them as of His Family, and treat them as his Children.</HI> GOD will take them up, and receive them under His Roof. Children are wont to gather to their Fathers Hou&s;e, while their Parents live to enjoy their Compa|ny, take their Advice, and receive their ble&s;&s;ing, &amp;c. Accordingly, when their Parents are removed by death, the LORD <HI>who is a dwelling place to His People in all Generati|ons,</HI> will grant them Re&s;t and Shelter by His gracious Pre&s;ence with them, and the care of His good Providence over them. They &s;hall abide under the &s;hadow of the Almighty, and that not &s;olitary, but having Him as a tender Father ready to a&s;&s;i&s;t and comfort them. GOD will not ca&s;t them off at &s;uch a time, No! but will fulfil that word to them, Heb. 13.5. <HI>I will never leave thee, nor for&s;ake thee.</HI> The Scripture refer'd to is &s;uppos'd to be GOD's word to Jo&s;hua after <HI>Mo&s;es's</HI> death, <HI>Jo&s;h.</HI> 1.5. <HI>I will not fail thee, nor for&s;ake thee.</HI> With this <HI>David</HI> encouraged his Son <HI>Solomon,</HI> when the time of his departure drew nigh, 1 Chron. 28.20. <HI>And David &s;aid to Solomon his &s;on, Be &s;trong, and of good courage, and do
<PB N="13" REF="003351_0015_0FF817852774D480">
it: fear not, nor be di&s;mayed, for the LORD GOD, even my GOD, will be with thee, he will not fail thee, nor for&s;ake thee</HI> &mdash; When this trouble is near, GOD will not &s;tand afar off, but will be found their pre&s;ent help. He will &s;ay to them, <HI>Fear not, for I am with thee, be not di&s;mayed, for I am thy GOD, I will &s;trengthen thee, yea I will help thee, yea I will uphold thee with the right hand of my righteou&s;ne&s;s <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">I&s;ai 41.10.</NOTE>.</HI> They &s;hall have freedom of acce&s;s to GOD, and may pour out their Com|plaints before Him with the liberty of Chil|dren; and GOD will hear them when be|moaning them&s;elves as <HI>Ephraim,</HI> under His cor|recting hand, and give that gracious an&s;wer, Jer. 31.20. <HI>Is Ephraim my dear &s;on? is he a plea|&s;ant child? for &s;ince I &s;pake again&s;t him, I do earne&s;tly remember him &s;till: therefore my bowels are troubled for him; I will &s;ure|ly have mercy upon him, &s;aith the LORD.</HI> This the word of GOD further declareth to us, that thro' the patience &amp; comfort of the Scrip|tures we might have hope: P&s;al. 103 13&mdash;18. <HI>Like as a father pitieth his children: &s;o the LORD pitieth them that fear him. For he knoweth our frame: he remembreth that we are du&s;t. As for man, his days are as gra&s;s: as a flower the field, &s;o be flouri&s;heth. For the wind pa&s;&s;eth over it, and it is gone; and the place thereof &s;hall know it no more. But the mercy of the LORD is from everla&s;ting to everla&s;ting upon them that fear him: and his
<PB N="14" REF="003351_0016_0FF817875878ADD0">
righteou&s;ne&s;s unto childrens children. To &s;uch as keep his covenant, and to tho&s;e that re|member his commandments to do them.</HI> Now, GOD's owning &amp; treating His People as Chil|dren may comprehend the particulars which follow, however, I &s;hall di&s;tinctly con&s;ider them.</P>
<P N="2">2. <HI>GOD will take them up, direct &amp; con|duct them in the ways which &s;hall be plea&s;ing to Him, and profitable for them.</HI> One great advantage we receive from wi&s;e and good Pa|rents is their Advice &amp; Coun&s;el. "Some of the Ancients &s;ay, that the word <HI>Pupil,</HI> which is from the <HI>Latin,</HI> &s;ignifieth, <HI>One without &s;ight,</HI> or wanting the apple or pupil of his Eyes; be|cau&s;e being depriv'd of his Parents, he wants the light of coun&s;el and direction, to carry him on in his cour&s;e thro' this World. What <HI>Mo|&s;es</HI> &s;pake to <HI>Hobab</HI> his father in law, is a truth of all good Parents to their Children, "They are to them <HI>in &s;tead of eyes,</HI> Numb. 10.31" <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">Caryl. on <HI>Job</HI> 6. 27.</NOTE> But now, when their eyes are clos'd by death, and their thoughts peri&s;h, GOD will direct His People, and guide them by His coun&s;el. He who is the <HI>Father of Lights</HI> with whom is no variablene&s;s, neither &s;hadow of turning, will en|lighten their darkne&s;s, and guide them with His Eye. When Children are thus bereaved, they are often in great perplexity, not knowing what to do: Jer. 10.23. &mdash; <HI>The way of man is not in him&s;elf: it is not in man to direct his &s;teps.</HI> The People of GOD are convinc'd of this truth, and accordingly obey that command, P&s;al. 37.5.
<PB N="15" REF="003351_0017_0FF81788EA4B54E0">
<HI>Commit thy way unto the Lord:</HI> &mdash; And find by happy experience that it is a command with promi&s;e. Prov. 3.6. <HI>In all thy ways acknow|ledge him, and he &s;hall direct thy paths.</HI> When thus for&s;aken, the <HI>Spirit of Adoption</HI> moves them to cry to the <HI>Eternal</HI> GOD, as, Jer. 3.4. <HI>My Father, Thou art the guide of my Youth.</HI> And GOD's ear is open to their cry. He will by the care of His watchful Providence, and by the influence of His Word &amp; Spirit effectually &s;ay to them, <HI>This is the way, walk ye in it,</HI> when they may be ready to turn to the right hand or to the left; &s;o that they &s;hall make no fatal mi&s;takes, nor be lo&s;t in that path which leads to de&s;truction. As to what concerns their Souls welfare, which is the One thing needful, GOD will <HI>guide them with his coun&s;el, and afterward receive them to glory</HI> <NOTE N="&Verbar;" PLACE="foot">P&s;al. 73</NOTE>. And as to what concerns their temporal Affairs, GOD will enable them to guide the&s;e with di&s;cretion, or &s;o over-rule even their mi&s;takes, as that <HI>all things &s;hall work together for their good</HI> <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">P&s;al. 112.5. Rom 8 28.</NOTE>.</P>
<P N="3">3. <HI>GOD will take them up to help, defend and provide for them.</HI> Parents are a great help and protection to their Children, however, when GOD's People are bereav'd of tho&s;e earth|ly helpers, they &s;hall not be left naked &amp; ex|pos'd. No. P&s;al. 115.11. <HI>The Lord is their help and their &s;hield.</HI> P&s;al. 10.14. &mdash;<HI>The poor com|mitteth him&s;elf unto thee, thou art the helper of the fatherle&s;s.</HI> GOD will be their guardian and protector, &s;o that they may boldly &s;ay,
<PB N="16" REF="003351_0018_0FF8178B2995FB18">
Heb. 13.6. <HI>The Lord is my helper, and I will not fear what man &s;hall do unto me.</HI> When Children are for&s;aken of their Parents, the Men of the World many times take the advantage to oppre&s;s them. <HI>Job</HI> complains, <HI>Ye overwhelm the fatherle&s;s,</HI> chap. 6.27. But now, GOD will &s;tand on their &s;ide, and if any injure them, He will re&s;ent and avenge it. Jer. 2.3.&mdash; <HI>All that devour him, &s;hall offend: &mdash; &s;aith the LORD.</HI> GOD hath forbidden us to <HI>afflict</HI> any Widow, or <HI>fatherle&s;s Child</HI> what&s;oever, Exod. 22.22. And a&s;&s;ureth us that if they cry to Him under &s;uch affliction, He will hear their cry, <HI>v.</HI> 23. How much rather will He hear when His Covenant-Children cry to Him under &s;uch oppre&s;&s;ion, and fulfil the threatning which follows: v. 24. <HI>My wrath &s;hall wax hot, and I will kill you with the &s;word; and your wives &s;hall be widows, and your children fatherle&s;s.</HI> GOD is their Judge, and He will do them right. P&s;al. 10.18. <HI>To judge the fatherle&s;s, and the oppre&s;&s;ed, that the man of the earth may no more oppre&s;s.</HI> It is one of His Titles as it were, whereby He makes Him&s;elf <HI>known</HI> to us, P&s;al. 146.9. <HI>The Lord relieveth the fatherle&s;s and widow.</HI> When they may be mo&s;t de&s;titute of humane aid, then will GOD be nigh to them, and in|compa&s;s them with His favour as with a &s;hield. Now they may &s;ing as P&s;al. 121.5. <HI>The Lord is thy keeper: the Lord is thy &s;hade upon thy right hand. v. 7. The Lord &s;hall pre&s;erve thee from all evil: he &s;hall pre&s;erve thy &s;oul.</HI> Yea, they &s;hall not only be defended from evil; but be well provided for and &s;upplied with that
<PB N="17" REF="003351_0019_0FF8178CE48797D0">
good which GOD &s;hall &s;ee mo&s;t needful &amp; &s;ui|table for them: their <HI>heavenly Father,</HI> who knoweth that they have need of the&s;e things, will give them <HI>bread</HI> to eat, and <HI>raiment</HI> to put on, until they are brought to His Hou&s;e which is eternal in the Heavens. <HI>David</HI> &s;ays, <HI>P&s;al.</HI> 37.25. I have been young, and now am old, yet <HI>have I not &s;een the righteous for&s;aken, nor his &s;eed begging bread.</HI> He had not, it may be, ob&s;erv'd the pious Children of godly Parents brought to begging; and tho' it is not uncom|mon now for GOD's Children to be poor in this World, yet they are not for&s;aken when brought thus low; no, GOD hath often given remarka|ble in&s;tances of His fatherly care of &s;uch as have had &s;carce any vi&s;ible means of &s;upport. He that hears the <HI>Ravens</HI> when they cry, and feeds them, will not &s;uffer His <HI>Covenant People</HI> to want the good things of this life which are pro|per for them; when they pray, as directed by their Lord &amp; Saviour, <HI>Give us this day our daily bread.</HI> How &s;trongly doth the Apo&s;tle argue, Rom. 8.32. <HI>He that &s;pared not his own Son, but delivered him up for us all, how &s;hall he not with him al&s;o freely give us all things?</HI> Let the bereaved be left in ever &s;uch poor and di&s;tre&s;&s;ed circum&s;tances, GOD's promi&s;e mu&s;t be fulfill'd, P&s;al. 84.11. <HI>The LORD God is a fun and &s;hield: the LORD will give grace and glory: no good thing will he withhold from them that walk uprightly.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4. <HI>GOD will take them up, and Comfort them under &s;uch a Bereavement.</HI> Pious Pa|rents are dear to &s;uch Children, and their lo&s;s in
<PB N="18" REF="003351_0020_0FF8178FA63EAE10">
them is in a manner irreparable as to the Crea|ture: who will, who can do for us as our Fa|thers that begat us, and our Mothers that bear us? GOD hath implanted in them a &s;trong and almo&s;t invincible affection towards the Offspring of their bodies, them&s;elves multiplied; &s;o that they &s;carce think any thing too much to do or &s;uffer for them: And their removal by death is often attended with peculiar difficulties. Agre|ably, we have that expre&s;&s;ion of di&s;tre&s;&s;ing &s;or|row, P&s;al. 35.14. <HI>I bowed down heavily, as one that mourneth for his Mother.</HI> But when they are in this mournful &s;tate, de&s;olate &amp; for&s;aken, GOD will vi&s;it them, and &s;peak comfortably to them; He will &s;it as One that comforteth the Mourners. Our Lord JESUS CHRIST who knows how to &s;peak a word in &s;ea&s;on to them that are weary, and hath been anointed with the oyl of gladne&s;s above His fellows, will give unto the&s;e mourners in Zion, <HI>beauty for a&s;hes, the oyl of joy for mourning</HI> <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">P&s;al. 45.7. I&s;ai. 61.3.</NOTE> There are many good words &s;poken to His People in the Scriptures, by which He revives the &s;pirits of the&s;e mourners, when He plea&s;eth. P&s;al. 68.5. <HI>A father of the fatherle&s;s, and a judge of the widows, is God in his holy habitation.</HI> Joh. 11.25. &mdash; <HI>I am the re&s;urrection, and the life.</HI> Matt. 9.2. &mdash; <HI>Son, be of good cheer, thy &s;ins be forgiven thee.</HI> Joh. 14.27. <HI>Peace I leave with you, my peace I give unto you: not as the world giveth, give I unto you. Let not your heart be troubled, neither let it be afraid.</HI>
<PB N="19" REF="003351_0021_0FF817921A29D488">
1 The&s;. 4.13, 14. Heb. 13.5. <HI>I will never leave thee</HI> &mdash;. And by His good Spirit, the Com|forter, He makes His word a word of life and comfort to their Souls.</P>
<P N="5">5. <HI>GOD will take them up, and Sanctify &s;uch Bereavement to them for &s;aving good.</HI> How grievous &s;oever the Cha&s;tening may be for the pre&s;ent, yet &s;hall it <HI>yield to them the peaceable fruit of righteou&s;ne&s;s.</HI> When GOD cha&s;ti&s;eth them it is in mea&s;ure, as a Father His Children. And by &s;uch afflictions GOD hum|bleth and proves them and doth them good for their latter end; &s;o that they have rea&s;on to &s;ay with him, P&s;al. 119.71. <HI>It is good for me that I have been afflicted</HI> &mdash;. Their iniquity is purged, their faith and patience are tryed and improv'd, and they grow in the experience of GOD's fatherly care &amp; pity towards them, which mu&s;t be for their great profit &amp; advantage.</P>
<P N="6">6. <HI>GOD will give them the Inheritance of Children, and take them up to dwell with Him for ever in Heaven.</HI> Rom. 8.17. <HI>If children, then heirs; heirs of God, &amp; joynt-heirs with Chri&s;t.</HI> GOD Him&s;elf will be their Portion, and fulfill the precious Promi&s;es of the New-Covenant to them: P&s;al. 16.5. <HI>The LORD is the portion of mine inheritance, and of my cup: thou main|taine&s;t my lot.</HI> They have cho&s;en Him as their Portion, and GOD hath given Him&s;elf to them as their GOD and Father in CHRIST, &amp; will accordingly ble&s;s them with all &s;piritual Ble&s;|&s;ings in heavenly things; yea, GOD will ble&s;s them indeed, even in the good things of this life, which their earthly Parents leave them; for
<PB N="20" REF="003351_0022_0FF8179515E0B540">
He gives the&s;e things to His cho&s;en People, be|ing mindful of His Covenant; and hence it is that <HI>a little which a righteous man hath, is better than the riches of many wicked,</HI> P&s;al. 37.16. In a word, GOD will not leave them, <HI>until he hath done that which he hath &s;poken to them of</HI> <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Gen. 28.15.</NOTE>; and put them into the full po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ion of all that good which is contain'd in the Promi&s;es of which they are the Heirs. GOD will be their <HI>guide to death,</HI> and when they fail here will receive them to the <HI>everla&s;ting Habi|tations</HI> which He hath prepar'd for them in Heaven, where they &s;hall have a perfect deli|verance from <HI>all evil,</HI> and the po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of <HI>all good</HI> in the full and everla&s;ting enjoyment of GOD the <HI>chief good;</HI> where they &s;hall meet their godly Parents gone before never to part again, and have every dark Providence clear'd up to their abundant &s;atisfaction. Joh. 14.2, 3. <HI>In my fathers hou&s;e are many man&s;ions; if it were not &s;o, I would have told you: I go to prepare a place for you. And if I go &amp; prepare a place for you, I will come again, and receive you unto my &s;elf, that where I am, there ye may be al&s;o.</HI> As Children, they &s;hall dwell in in the Hou&s;e of the LORD for ever, and there will GOD make the &s;ulle&s;t manife&s;tations of His fatherly love to them. Agreably, in our <HI>Ver&s;ion</HI> of the <HI>&s;inging P&s;alms,</HI> the words are thus rendred. <HI>Yet will JEHOVAH gathering, unto Him&s;elf me take.</HI> And &s;urely they need no more to compleat their happine&s;s: Ever to be with the LORD, is to be eternally ble&s;&s;ed.</P>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="application">
<PB N="21" REF="003351_0023_0FF817972E861090">
<HEAD>APPLICATION</HEAD>
<P>USE I. Mu&s;t our Fathers &amp; Mothers for|&s;ake us, <HI>&s;ee here what an evil &amp; bitter thing &s;in is, by the fruit of it.</HI> It is a root of bitter|ne&s;s bearing wormwood &amp; gall. It kills even them that were mo&s;t dear to us, and &s;eparates the neare&s;t Relations; it puts lover &amp; friend far from us, and our Acquaintance into darkne&s;s. It is &s;in that hath brought mi&s;ery and death into the World. Rom. 6.23.
<HI>The wages of &s;in is death.</HI> O let us then turn from all &s;in as the abominable thing which our &s;ouls hate: Let us under &s;uch Bereavements, mourn for our <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"> with that godly &s;orrow which worketh Repentance, and &s;o fly from them unto JESUS CHRIST, who <HI>&s;aves his People from their &s;ins: Ble&s;&s;ed are they who thus mourn; for they &s;hall be comforted.</HI></P>
<P N="2">II. Mu&s;t our Fathers &amp; Mothers for&s;ake us; <HI>Then we &s;hould prize them and do our Duty towards them while we enjoy them; and humble our &s;elves under GOD's correcting Hand, when they are taken from us.</HI> We are very much oblig'd to our Parents: In them GOD hath made a wife and gracious provi&s;ion for our continuance &amp; comfort in the World; Indeed <HI>earthly Fathers</HI> are but the <HI>fathers of our fle&s;h,</HI> which is al&s;o GOD's Creature; GOD is the <HI>Father of Spirits,</HI> He forms the Spirit of Man within him; however, they are in&s;truments in GOD's hand, of our being and
<PB N="22" REF="003351_0024_0FF81798CB5B68E0">
well being here. What creature &s;o helple&s;s as Man in his Infant &s;tate? In an&s;wer to which, we have the tender love &amp; care of our Parents: Thus did GOD make us to hope when we were upon our Mother's brea&s;ts, who mu&s;t have peri&s;h'd if left to our &s;elves. Many and great are the benefits which we receive from our Pa|rents, e&s;pecially from pious Parents both rela|ting to this and a better life, in our comfortable Sub&s;i&s;tance, early Dedication to GOD, Educa|tion, &amp;c. Certainly then, we &s;hould highly e&s;teem and dearly love them; we &s;hould ho|nour and obey them in the LORD, as the fifth Commandment requireth, which is the fir&s;t Commandment "with a &s;pecial Promi&s;e of life and pro&s;perity" annexed to it. Eph. 6. <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>Honour thy father and mother, (which is the fir&s;t commandment with promi&s;e) That it may be well with thee, and thou may&s;t live long on the earth.</HI> And if they live to &s;tand in need of our help thro' the infirmities of age, or upon other accounts, <HI>We &s;hould &s;hew piety at home, and requite our Parents: for that is good and acceptable before God,</HI> 1 Tim. 5.4. And when GOD removes them from us by death, we &s;hould &s;ee His hand &s;tretched out again&s;t us, and humble our &s;elves under it; we &s;hould neither de&s;pi&s;e the Cha&s;ti&s;ement of the LORD, nor yet &s;aint when rebuked of Him; but be in &s;ubjection to the Father of Spirits that we may live, and enjoy His pre&s;ence with us when our earthly Parents for&s;ake us. And therefore, as it hath plea&s;ed GOD to take my <HI>aged and ho|noured Father</HI> from my head, who&s;e memory
<PB N="23" REF="003351_0025_0FF8179A89D332A0">
will ever be precious to me; I be&s;eech you, Brethren, that ye &s;trive together with me in your Prayers to GOD for me; that I may be enabled &s;o to attend the&s;e Duties, as to give glory to GOD, and to be an En&s;ample to the Flock. I acknowlege my &s;elf unworthy of the honour &amp; privilege I enjoy'd in &s;uch a Parent, and wou'd aba&s;e my &s;elf before the LORD, that I made no better improvement of my advantages, e&s;pecially on &s;piritual accounts: And while I cry after him, <HI>my Father, my Fa|ther,</HI> the chariot of I&s;rael, and the hor&s;emen thereof I wou'd earne&s;tly &s;eek to GOD our <HI>heavenly Father,</HI> that the Spirit which was on him may be given unto me, that I may exalt <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"> Father's GOD, and follow His Servant as he followed JESUS CHRIST. May the LORD be the GOD and Judge of the Widow; may He take up the Fatherle&s;s into the Arms of His everla&s;ting Mercy, and ble&s;s them with the Ble&s;&s;ings of His well ordered &amp; &s;ure Covenant: And may we all be <HI>followers of them who thro' faith and patience inherit the promi&s;es.</HI></P>
<P N="3">III.<HI>We &s;hould be above all things con|cerned to make &s;ure of this, that the everla&s;t|ing Father is our GOD and Father in CHRIST JESUS.</HI> Our earthly Parents are mortal, and mu&s;t be taken from us by death; but GOD is the &s;ame and His years fail not; He lives for ever the Hope of His I&s;rael and the saviour thereof in all times of trouble: Let us then return to Him from whom we have departed by the Apo&s;tacy, confe&s;&s;ing we have
<PB N="24" REF="003351_0026_0FF8179D5545D8B8">
&s;inned in His Sight, and are unworthy to be called His Children; let us cry to Him to ex|tend His fatherly pity and mercy to us in and by His <HI>beloved Son, whom in the fulne&s;s of time He &s;ent forth made of a woman, made under the law, to redeem them that were un|der the law, that we might receive the A|doption of Sons,</HI> Gal. 4.4, 5. Let us by His Grace heartily con&s;ent to receive JESUS CHRIST according to the New Covenent, then His Father will be our Father, and His GOD our GOD <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Joh 20. 17.</NOTE> Let us <HI>ask</HI> of GOD His <HI>Holy Spirit,</HI> that being born again, not of cor|ruptible Seed, but of incorruptible by the word of GOD which liveth and abideth for ever, we may bear His Image, and bring forth that fruit whereby our heavenly Father &s;hall be glorified. Let us reverence and honour, obey and &s;ubmit to Him in all things, and be fol|lowers of Him as dear Children: Then we may rejoyce in Him under all &s;orrowful Bereave|ments, and &s;ay, <HI>The LORD lives, and ble&s;&s;ed be my Rock.</HI> We may comfort our&s;elves with the&s;e words, and be a&s;&s;ur'd that what ever is taken from us, GOD Him&s;elf who is <HI>all in all,</HI> will never for&s;ake us. He will come unto us, and make His abode with us while in this World, and when we &s;hall be here no more, will receive us to His Hou&s;e which is eternal in the Heavens, where we &s;hall be for ever comforted in His Pre&s;ence, <HI>in who&s;e Pre&s;ence is fulne&s;s of joy, and at who&s;e right hand there are plea&s;ures for ever more.</HI></P>
<P N="4"><PB N="25" REF="003351_0027_0FF8179FF2891688">IV. I wou'd clo&s;e the &s;ubject <HI>with a word of Exhortation, directed to Parents and Children.</HI></P>
<P N="1">I. <HI>To Parents,</HI> in a few particulars.</P>
<P N="1">1. Be Exhorted, <HI>Early to Pray for your Children, and in this way commend them to be Care &amp; Ble&s;&s;ing of the Everla&s;ting Father.</HI></P>
<P>It is one great Privilege which belongs to the Relation of Parents in Covenant with GOD, ble&s;s their Children in the Name of the LORD, by asking His Ble&s;&s;ing for them. And &s;urely the con&s;ideration of your Mortality &s;hould quicken you to begin this Duty &s;o &s;oon as you know they begin to live, and to conti|nue in&s;tant in it with all per&s;everance; for when you are remov'd, you will not be ac|quainted with their condition as now you are, and if faithful, will be taken up from them to Prai&s;e GOD in His Temple above. Now then, lay up a &s;tock of <HI>Prayers</HI> for them which may come down in <HI>Ble&s;&s;ings</HI> upon them, even after your decea&s;e. You have been in&s;trumen|tal of conveying &s;in and death to them. P&s;al. 51.5. <HI>Behold, I was &s;hapen in iniquity, and in &s;in did my Mother conceive me.</HI> O cry to GOD then that they may experience the power of the <HI>New Birth,</HI> and that being clean&s;ed from their &s;ins by the Blood and Spirit of CHRIST, they may live to GOD here, and be prepared to follow you to Heaven, Thus
<PB N="26" REF="003351_0028_0FF817A187BECDA8">
<HI>David</HI> pray'd for <HI>Solomon,</HI> 1 Chron. 29.19. <HI>Give unto Solomon my &s;on a perfect heart to keep thy commandments</HI> &mdash;. Seeing you know not the day of your death, how &s;oon and &s;uddenly it may come upon you; attend this Duty daily, <HI>in &s;ecret,</HI> and <HI>in your families;</HI> yea, <HI>take them with you</HI> &s;ometimes in your <HI>Retirements,</HI> and let them &s;ee your concern for them in your &s;ervent Prayers to GOD on their behalf. Thus to attend your duty will be one likely way of enjoying them as Ble&s;&s;ings of GOD to you while you live; and in this way, you may with the more comfortable a&s;|&s;urance commit them to the care of the ever-living GOD, when you leave them at death.</P>
<P N="2">2. <HI>Give them up to GOD in Bapti&s;m,</HI> and thus do your endeavour to bring them under the wing and ble&s;&s;ing of the everla&s;ting Cove|nant e&s;tabli&s;h'd with GOD's People, and their Seed in CHRIST JESUS.</P>
<P>As Children are virtually in their Parents before they are begotten and born into the World, &s;o it hath plea&s;ed GOD to include Pa|rents together with their Children in the Cove|nant. Thus it was under the fir&s;t Covenant, the <HI>Covenant of Works</HI> made with <HI>Adam,</HI> "not for him&s;elf only, but for his Po&s;terity". And thus it is under the <HI>New Covenant,</HI> the Covenant of Grace. GOD promi&s;ed <HI>Abraham,</HI> Gen. 17.7. <HI>I will e&s;tabli&s;h my covenant be|tween me and thee, and thy &s;eed after thee, in their generations for an everla&s;ting covenant;
<PB N="27" REF="003351_0029_0FF817A49E6E5050">
to be a God unto thee, and to thy &s;eed after thee.</HI> Which ble&s;&s;ing is come on the believing Gentiles thro' JESUS CHRIST, <HI>Gal.</HI> 3.14. Let Parents then under the realizing view of the frailty of this life, make ha&s;t to lay hold of GOD's Covenant, and to give up them&s;elves and their Seed to Him as their GOD, and that with their whole hearts; that whatever changes pa&s;s over your Hou&s;es, you may rejoyce with <HI>David,</HI> 2 Sam. 23.5. <HI>Although my hou&s;e be not &s;o with God; yet he hath made with me in everla&s;ting covenant, ordered in all things and &s;ure: for this is all my &s;alvation, and all my de&s;ire, although he make it not to grow.</HI> In this way, <HI>devote them to GOD,</HI> that He may own them as His Children, and take them up when you for&s;ake them: In this way, <HI>bring them to CHRIST</HI> for His ble&s;&s;ing, who &s;aid, <HI>Suffer little Children, and forbid them not to come unto me: for of &s;uch is the kingdom of heaven,</HI> Mat. 19.14. In this way, <HI>&s;eek to</HI> GOD that they may be <HI>Saved by the wa&s;hing of Regeneration, and the renewing of the Holy Gho&s;t.</HI> Indeed, we can't &s;ay that all who are vi&s;ibly in Covenant obtain the invi&s;ible Grace and &s;aving Ble&s;&s;ings of the Covenant: <HI>For they are not all I&s;rael, which are of I&s;rael,</HI> Rom. 9.6. Sad experience teach|eth us that not a few have with profane <HI>E&s;au</HI> de&s;pi&s;ed the <HI>Birth-right.</HI> However, this is one of the means of Grace which that GOD hath appointed who alone can command the Ble&s;&s;ing; and the con&s;ideration of the uncertainty of our own lives as well as the lives of our Children,
<PB N="28" REF="003351_0030_0FF817A74D233478">
&s;hould make us &s;peedy and very &s;erious in this Covenant tran&s;action with GOD on their be|half, that we may in faith plead the Promi&s;es of GOD's Covenant for them, when we are a|bout to be taken from them.</P>
<P N="3">3. <HI>Teach them the Will of GOD, and call upon them to Choo&s;e that good Part which can't be taken away.</HI></P>
<P><HI>All fle&s;h is as gra&s;s,&mdash; but the word of the LORD endureth for ever</HI> <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot">1 Pet 1.24, 25.</NOTE>. O do your utmo&s;t then that they may know the Scrip|tures from their childhood, and have the laws of GOD written upon their hearts. Labour to in&s;till the principles of Religion into them, and teach them early how they mu&s;t fear and &s;erve the LORD, while you look to GOD to fulfill His promi&s;e: I&s;ai. 54.13. <HI>All thy children &s;hall be taught of the LORD</HI>&mdash;. Shew them their &s;in and mi&s;ery by the Fall, and the only remedy provided in JESUS CHRIST, the only Name given among Men whereby we can be &s;av'd. Call upon them to know the GOD of their Fathers, and to choo&s;e Him as their GOD. Urge them to make &s;ure of an Intere&s;t in CHRIST, and the Ble&s;&s;ings of the Covenant; to Repent of their Sins, and make ha&s;te to keep GOD's Commandments; that He may never leave them, and that in Him the unchangable GOD, they may have an unfailing Friend and everla&s;ting Portion. You
<PB N="29" REF="003351_0031_0FF817A99A331B88">
know not how &s;oon you may be &s;ilent in the Grave: O do not delay then to &s;peak to them about the concerns of their Souls, and to teach them the good knowledge of the LORD, that they may be wi&s;e for Eternity &amp; to Salvation!</P>
<P N="4">4. <HI>Go before them,</HI> while GOD continueth you with them, <HI>in an holy Exemplary Con|ver&s;ation.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Walk before GOD</HI> within your hou&s;e with a <HI>perfect heart,</HI> and <HI>before them,</HI> in a <HI>perfect way;</HI> for it is natural and common for Chil|dren to imitate their Parents. It is true, they &s;tand in need of <HI>&s;upernatural Grace,</HI> to enable them to follow your pious Examples; how|ever, the duty is your's, and you mu&s;t di&s;charge it, looking to GOD to turn their feet to His Te&s;timonies. Be exhorted then to &s;et the great and weighty matters of GOD's law before your Children, not only in <HI>verbal In&s;tructions,</HI> but in a <HI>living Pattern;</HI> that they may be en|couraged to <HI>follow your faith, con&s;idering the end of your conver&s;ation.</HI> It may be you have but a little time to be with them, O endea|vour then to do much, by living much to the honour of GOD, the little time that remains! Take heed you do not lay a &s;tumbling-block before them by living in the <HI>Omi&s;&s;ion of Duty,</HI> of Family-prayer, of the &s;trict Ob&s;erva|tion of the Lord's-day, of a devout Attendance on the Lord's Table, &amp;c. Or, <HI>in the Commi&s;&s;ion of Sin,</HI> of profane&s;s, of intemperance, lying, di&s;hone&s;ty in dealing, &amp;c. left they fall after
<PB N="30" REF="003351_0032_0FF817ABEBDED9A8">
your Example, and GOD <HI>vi&s;it the iniquity of the Fathers upon the Children.</HI> O do not walk in that broad way which leads to de|&s;truction, left they follow you, and you have a dreadful meeting in Hell; but in that narrow way which leads to life, that you may have a joyful meeting in Heaven.</P>
<P N="5">5. <HI>Endeavour to leave your Children with GOD, when you for&s;ake them; and do what you can that they may live in Peace among them&s;elves.</HI></P>
<P>The great work we have to do when we come to die, is to commit our departing Spirits into the Hands of JESUS CHRIST, and &s;o to re&s;ign our lives to GOD by Him as a free-will Offering; but this is not all, we &s;hou'd al&s;o commit our dear Relatives, and in particular our Children, to the care of the living GOD, when we are leaving them. If you under&s;tand that word as an exhortation and promi&s;e to GOD's People, it may be fitly applied here, Jer 49.11. <HI>Leave thy fatherle&s;s children, I will pre&s;erve them alive, and let thy widows tru&s;t in me.</HI> Now then commend them to GOD in a &s;olemn manner, and if GOD give you the opportunity, Charge them to keep His Covenant, that they may happily find that GOD is the GOD of His People, and of their Seed in their Generati|ons. And in order to their obtaining the gra|cious Pre&s;ence of GOD with them, you &s;hou'd do what you can that they may dwell together in Unity; for thus runs the promi&s;e, 2 Cor
<PB N="31" REF="003351_0033_0FF817AF18EC5B18">
13.11. &mdash;<HI>Live in Peace: and the God of love and peace &s;hall be with you.</HI> And here it may not be ami&s;s to &s;ay, prudently and &s;ea&s;o|nably &s;ettle your Affairs, that there may be no occa&s;ion of unhappy divi&s;ion and alienation upon temporal accounts.</P>
<P>In a word, <HI>Whatever your hand finds to do</HI> for the welfare of your Children, <HI>do it with your might;</HI> for there is no work nor knowledge in the Grave whither you are going. If there be any Commands or Charges needful for you to give, and them to receive, delay them not, left you be prevented by Death. If you are middle Aged, you may not pre&s;ume you have time enough before you; for not a few die in their full &s;trength: And if GOD hath &s;pared you to old Age, you had need make ha&s;te to attend your duty in the&s;e &amp; other re&s;pects, that when Death comes, you may take leave of your Chil|dren with a comfortable hope that GOD will take them up and ble&s;s them, as He did <HI>I&s;aac</HI> after his Father's death, Gen. 25. 11. <HI>And it came to pa&s;s after the death of Abraham, that God ble&s;&s;ed his &s;on I&s;aac;</HI> and that you &s;hall have a Seed to <HI>&s;erve</HI> GOD on <HI>earth,</HI> when you are <HI>call'd</HI> up to <HI>Prai&s;e</HI> Him in <HI>Heaven.</HI></P>
<P N="2">II. Let the Exhortation be directed, <HI>to Children.</HI></P>
<P N="1">1. <HI>Be thankful to GOD if He continueth your Parents to you after you are grown up.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="32" REF="003351_0034_0FF817B186ECDF78">It is the &s;orrowful ca&s;e of many, that their Parents for&s;ake them while very young: If it be otherwi&s;e with you, humbly ble&s;s GOD, and con&s;ider how you may be&s;t &s;hew your grateful &s;en&s;e of &s;uch a benefit, and improve it to the honour of GOD, and your own advan|tage. And remember, you are in an e&s;pecial. manner oblig'd thus to expre&s;s your thankful|ne&s;s, if your Parents have not only &s;ome <HI>ex|ternal re&s;emblance</HI> of GOD upon them, who is the Father of all, in the authority this Re|lation gives them over you; but al&s;o his <HI>moral Image</HI> in them, which is created <HI>in righteou&s;ne&s;s and true holine&s;s:</HI> The pre&s;ence of &s;uch Parents who have GOD graciou&s;ly pre&s;ent with them, is a great &s;avour indeed. Happy, thrice happy the Children! who are thus favour'd of the LORD, know their Privi|lege, and wi&s;ely improve it.</P>
<P N="2">2. <HI>Do your utmo&s;t that you may be Ble&s;&s;ings and Comforts to them, while they live.</HI></P>
<P>Altho' you are grown to years capable of choo&s;ing &amp; acting for your &s;elves, and remov'd into di&s;tinct Families, yet your obligation to honour your Fathers and Mothers abides with the Relation; tho' indeed the authority of Pa|rents and obedience of Children are to be exer|ci&s;ed after a different manner: Do you then expre&s;s your filial duty in a manner becoming your riper Age, and labour to be helpful to
<PB N="33" REF="003351_0035_0FF817B405FA3E30">
your Parents, even when you are remov'd from under their immediate care. Now endeavour to be under GOD <HI>their Staff,</HI> when they de|cline thro' age; and do what you can to &s;weeten and <HI>brighten</HI> the <HI>evil days</HI> which are come upon them, by your good carriage. O de&s;pi&s;e them not when they are old; but &s;uccour them under their infirmities, and let them now have &s;ome good fruit of their unwearied care and pains with you. <HI>Heavenly Father! for|give our &s;inful defects for Thy Son's &s;ake, with who&s;e perfect Obedience Thou wa&s;t ever well plea&s;ed.</HI></P>
<P N="3">3. <HI>When your Parents for&s;ake you, Look to GOD to take you up.</HI></P>
<P>Prepare for &s;uch a dark hour by taking care to give up your &s;elves to the living GOD, as your GOD and Father, by receiving all the good you can from your Parents, and doing all the good you can to them, while you are con|tinued to each other. Live under the realizing view of their and your own Mortality. Let their commands, and e&s;pecially their dying charges have great weight with you. And when they are taken from you, go to GOD in the Name of CHRIST, and depend on Him for all that light and grace, direction and help which you need. Thus you &s;hall find Him the <HI>Father of Mercies</HI> to you; He will take you up, and make up your lo&s;s in Him&s;elf, and in His CHRTST.</P>
<TRAILER>FINIS</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
